- Initial custom-image endpoint run attempt failed because HF auth was not loaded. User clarified `.env` can be used; `.env` contains `HF_TOKEN` declared with `export`, which must be normalized internally without printing the value.
- Retried custom-image HF Endpoint using `.env` auth. Reused/updated endpoint `reasoning-pruning-gemma4-e2b-it` with model `avreymi/reasoning-pruning-gemma-4-E2B-it`, custom image `docker.io/avreymi/reasoning-pruning-gemma4-endpoint:gemma4-e2b-it-20260521`, health route `/health`, env `MODEL_PATH=/repository`, AWS `us-east-1`, `nvidia-l4`, `x1`, one replica. Resume succeeded but endpoint stayed `initializing` with 0 ready replicas for 45 minutes; no minimal request was run. Endpoint was paused to avoid cost. HF Hub API exposed only sanitized status, not detailed container logs.
- Researched Hugging Face Jobs/Python Jobs after user asked to run Gemma4 as a job. HF Jobs can run arbitrary commands or UV Python scripts on selected HF hardware with Docker image/UV deps, env vars, encrypted secrets, logs/status/cancel, timeouts, and optional Hub repo/bucket mounts. Strong fit for one-off Gemma4 batch generation because it avoids HF provider/TGI/default endpoint serving support and can install the validated Transformers git-main stack. Private model access should work with `--secrets HF_TOKEN` if the token has repo access. Job filesystems are ephemeral, so smoke tests can print to logs but real outputs must upload/mount to a private dataset repo/bucket.
- Prepared minimal HF Jobs Gemma4 smoke script at `/tmp/opencode/gemma4_hf_job_minimal.py` with PEP 723 deps and one tiny prompt. After user clarified `HF_TOKEN` is in `.env`, loaded it safely without printing secrets, authenticated HF CLI, and launched minimal paid HF Job. Job `6a0e9756ac8efd7fbbb2ad43` on `a10g-large` completed successfully. It detected `NVIDIA A10G`, downloaded `model.safetensors` (~10.2G), loaded weights, and ran inference with `avreymi/reasoning-pruning-gemma-4-E2B-it` using source Transformers stack. Output decoded only the prompt (`Solve briefly: If x=2, what is x+3?`) rather than answer, so infrastructure works; next issue is prompt/chat-template generation/decoding. Recommended second job: use `processor.apply_chat_template(..., add_generation_prompt=True)`, decode only generated tokens after input length, and increase `max_new_tokens` to 64.
- Ran second paid HF Jobs Gemma4 smoke test with chat template and generated-token-only decoding. Job `6a0e98d93fef25139d6ca713` on `a10g-large` completed successfully. It loaded `Gemma4ForConditionalGeneration`/`Gemma4Processor` from `avreymi/reasoning-pruning-gemma-4-E2B-it` using Transformers git commit `52b82b299171721fbe7b04fe056187f7aed2e2cc`. GPU observed: NVIDIA A10G with ~22.30 GiB visible. Prompt token count 23, generated token count 24, generated text: `If $x=2$, then $x+3 = 2+3 = 5$.` This confirms HF Jobs can run the regular Gemma4 model and produce real assistant output when using `processor.apply_chat_template(..., add_generation_prompt=True, tokenize=True, return_dict=True, return_tensors="pt")` and decoding only `output_ids[0][input_len:]`. Future scripts should use `dtype=` instead of deprecated `torch_dtype=`.
- Created `docs/model-interface-options.md`, a detailed model-interface summary covering serverless/providers, default endpoints, TGI, custom Docker endpoint, local generation, and HF Jobs. After correction, updated it to state the chosen workflow is the normal config-driven runner; the standalone script was deleted because it bypassed architecture.
